<subSubSection pageId="6" pageNumber="5" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="6.[192,1440,482,858]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,349,482,506]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">Discussion.</emphasis>
The leoni species group is composed of 7 species, 6 of which inhabit the Neotropical region (
<bibRefCitation author="Borkent, A. &amp; G. R. Spinelli" box="[200,536,514,538]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" refId="ref13097" refString="Borkent, A., and G. R. Spinelli. 2007. Neotropical Ceratopogonidae (Diptera: Insecta). In: J. Adis, J. R. Arias, G. Rueda-Delgado, and K. M. Wantzen (eds). Aquatic biodiversity in Latin America (ABLA). Vol. 4. Pensoft; Sofia-Moscow. 198 p." type="book" year="2007">Borkent and Spinelli 2007</bibRefCitation>
). The 7 
<superScript attach="left" box="[630,645,513,527]" fontSize="6" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">th</superScript>
species, 
<taxonomicName authority="Wirth" authorityName="Wirth" authorityYear="1952" box="[756,957,514,538]" class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Culicoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="reevesi">
<emphasis box="[756,775,515,538]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[791,872,515,538]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">reevesi</emphasis>
Wirth
</taxonomicName>
, is known in the Nearctic region from Arizona, California, New 
<collectingRegion box="[508,596,546,570]" country="Mexico" name="Mexico" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">Mexico</collectingRegion>
and Utah (
<bibRefCitation author="Grogan, W. L., Jr. &amp; G. R. Spinelli &amp; R. A. Phillips &amp; D. L. Woodward" box="[736,970,546,570]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" pagination="433 - 438" refId="ref13850" refString="Grogan, W. L., Jr., G. R. Spinelli, R. A. Phillips, and D. L. Woodward. 2004. The male of Culicoides reevesi Wirth, with a redescription of the female and new seasonal activity, distribution, and biting records (Diptera: Ceratopogonidae). Western North American Naturalist 64: 433 - 438." type="journal article" year="2004">Grogan et al. 2004</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Borkent, A. &amp; W. L. Grogan, Jr." box="[982,1309,546,570]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" pagination="1 - 48" refId="ref13013" refString="Borkent, A., and W. L. Grogan, Jr. 2009. Catalog of the New World biting midges north of Mexico (Diptera: Ceratopogonidae). Zootaxa 2273: 1 - 48." type="journal article" year="2009">Borkent and Grogan 2009</bibRefCitation>
). The only species previously known from this group in 
<collectingCountry box="[730,817,578,602]" name="Mexico" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">Mexico</collectingCountry>
is 
<taxonomicName authority="Ortiz" authorityName="Ortiz" authorityYear="1954" box="[849,1075,578,602]" class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Culicoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gabaldoni">
<emphasis box="[849,868,579,602]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[879,1001,578,602]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">gabaldoni</emphasis>
Ortiz
</taxonomicName>
, which is widely distributed in the Neotropical region (
<bibRefCitation author="Borkent, A. &amp; G. R. Spinelli" box="[480,804,610,634]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" refId="ref13097" refString="Borkent, A., and G. R. Spinelli. 2007. Neotropical Ceratopogonidae (Diptera: Insecta). In: J. Adis, J. R. Arias, G. Rueda-Delgado, and K. M. Wantzen (eds). Aquatic biodiversity in Latin America (ABLA). Vol. 4. Pensoft; Sofia-Moscow. 198 p." type="book" year="2007">Borkent and Spinelli 2007</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[192,1440,482,858]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Wirth" authorityYear="1974" box="[240,432,642,666]" class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Culicoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leoni">
<emphasis box="[240,432,642,666]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">Culicoides leoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from other species in the leoni group by the following combination of characters: sensilla coeloconica on flagellomeres 1, 5-8; female wing length 0.63 mm; wing pattern with the caudal extension of the post-stigmatic pale spot not oblique in cell r3 and usually connected to vein M1; smaller pale spot on r-m crossvein; one pale spot in cell M1 near base; and distal pale spot in anal cell abutting wing margin.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="6.[192,1440,482,858]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">
This species was previously known from 
<collectingCountry box="[720,822,802,826]" name="Ecuador" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Borkent, A. &amp; G. R. Spinelli" box="[834,1150,802,826]" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" refId="ref13097" refString="Borkent, A., and G. R. Spinelli. 2007. Neotropical Ceratopogonidae (Diptera: Insecta). In: J. Adis, J. R. Arias, G. Rueda-Delgado, and K. M. Wantzen (eds). Aquatic biodiversity in Latin America (ABLA). Vol. 4. Pensoft; Sofia-Moscow. 198 p." type="book" year="2007">Borkent and Spinelli 2007</bibRefCitation>
), and 
<collectingCountry box="[1217,1332,802,826]" name="Colombia" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">Colombia</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Spinelli, G. R. &amp; E. Santamaria &amp; O. L. Cabrera &amp; M. M. Ronderos &amp; M. F. Suarez" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" pagination="81 - 92" refId="ref15036" refString="Spinelli, G. R., E. Santamaria, O. L. Cabrera, M. M. Ronderos, and M. F. Suarez. 2009. Five new species of Culicoides Latreille described from Colombia, yielding a new species list and country records (Diptera: Ceratopogonidae). Memorias do Instituto Oswaldo Cruz 104: 81 - 92." type="journal article" year="2009">Spinelli et al. 2009</bibRefCitation>
). We provide the first records of 
<taxonomicName authorityName=": Wirth" authorityYear="1974" box="[716,808,834,858]" class="Insecta" family="Ceratopogonidae" genus="Culicoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="5" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="leoni">
<emphasis box="[716,735,835,858]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[748,808,834,858]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">leoni</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[879,971,834,858]" name="Mexico" pageId="6" pageNumber="5">Mexico</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
